# Performance Improvements and Delta Lake in 2.4.1

## Intellio DataOps 2.4.1 Release 

Similar to 2.4.0, this release primarily focuses on quality of life features – as well as a few important performance improvements and bugfixes. Here are a few of the major additions: 

* Performance and Stability Optimizations 
* Combined Source List Filter 
* Delta Lake Output 
* External API Routes 

## Performance and Stability Optimizations 

When helping clients debug stability issues in 2.4.0, we noticed a number of storage patterns that Spark was using as default were causing significant performance and scalability issues.

We're providing a deep dive overview here for those interested, but the summary boils down to a restructuring of the raw files stored in the datalake which leverages metadata about the dynamically allocated infrastructure, refresh type, and a new target file size parameter to do some math and auto-optimize the storage layer more effectively to improve scalability on large datasets.

### Key refresh sources 

Before: hub table bucketed on s\_key into fixed number of buckets: \(\# of spark worker nodes\) \* 4  

Problem:  complex processing logic \(e.g. window functions, aggregate lookups\) caused spark engine to arbitrarily repartition the data into default partition count \(200\) for optimal processing \(e.g. using partition columns used by each window function\). This resulted in significant skeweness of the data distribution across parquet files:  

* 10% of files are very large \(several GB each\) and represent 90% of data 
* 90% of files are very small \(&lt; 10MB\) and represent 10% of data 
* Random distribution of files across buckets  

Secondary issue with formula we used to calculate \# of available executors did not take into account cluster node type and custom-configured clusters  

Impact: This skeweness significantly extended data processing time and prevented cluster scaling due to uneven partitioning. Majority of executors assigned small partitions would finish quickly and idle, and few executors handling large partitions would take very long time to finish. This also impacted stability of the cluster as large partitions would overload node RAM and require frequent memory to disc spills. Both read and write performance is impacted by this.  

Solution:  

1. Added new system\_configuration parameter : target-parquet-file-size, defaulted to 256MB 
2. Captured and stored the size of each source hub table \(visible on source list UI page\)   
3. Updated formula to calculate available \# of executors using \# of available cluster CPUs  
4. Calculated target \# of buckets based on above values of 1,2 and 3. For example, source with hub\_table size of 10G and default parquet size 256M will be saved into 40 buckets, with 1 parquet file per bucket 
5. Added source parameter to disable bucketing \(experimental\) 
6. Added cluster size check that writes warning in log when cluster size is over- or undersized for the calculated \# of partitions. Ideal target: 1 executor per dataframe partition 
7. Partitioned hub table sources \(None, Timestamp and Sequence refresh type\) with keep\_current attributes 

Before: before overwriting the hub table, final dataframe is coalesced into \(\# of spark worker nodes\) \* 4 partitions. Hive table is partitioned on s\_input\_id 

Problem:  as the size of hub table and \# of batches \(inputs\) grow, static number of dataframe partitions becomes too small and inefficient :  

* partition sizes are too large, leading to large files  
* Each partition contains mix of data from multiple batches \(s\_input\_id\) 

Secondary issue with formula we used to calculate \# of available executors did not take into account cluster node type and custom-configured clusters  

Impact:  similar to key refresh type, uneven partitioning leads to skewness in processing and inefficient parquet file sizes. Some executors are busy writing multiple small files across multiple hive table partitions, others are overloaded by writing single large file and take very long time to finish. This also impacts cluster stability in the same manner as described for keyed sources. Both read and write performance is impacted by this.  

Solution:  

1. Using new added parameters & calculations described in section I, p.1-3 above, calculate target \# of partitions to generate optimal file sizes. For example, source with hub\_table size of 10G, partitioned into 10 batches \(input\_ids\) with default target parquet size 256M will be saved into 10 hive table partitions, with 4 parquet file in each partition 
2. Added cluster size check that writes warning in log when cluster size is over- or undersized for the calculated \# of partitions. Ideal target: 1 executor per dataframe partition 
3. CDC & Enriched file partitioning and format optimization 

Before: CDC files were saved as avro. Both CDC and Enriched files were split into static \(\# of spark worker nodes\) \* 4 chunks 

Problem:  avro file type is roughly 50% less performant vs. Parquet when comparing over full read-write cycle, mostly due to avro file sizes being larger.  Static \# of partitions \(\# of spark worker nodes\) \* 4 was optimized for 4 core nodes, and didn’t work with custom cluster configurations. 

Impact:  ~50% performance impact on read-write between CDC  and Enrichment phases. Nodes with less than 4 cores generated too many files, nodes larger than 4 cores generated too few files  

Solution: 

1. Updated formula to calculate available \# of executors using \# of available cluster CPUs 
2. Changed output file format for CDC phase to parquet 
3. Added automatic detection of file type \(avro/parquet\) during Enrichment – no data migration is required 
4. Optimized UI/UX refresh cycle for source status, Process and Inputs pages 

Before: Data on Process and Inputs pages was fully refreshed every 5 sec. Source status was also dynamically calculated every 5 sec together with inputs page refresh 

Problem:  Process and source status queries are complex and when multiple users have these tabs open, can easily overload postgres database and lead to API crash restart.  

Impact:  API crash disrupts UX and spark job communications and risks failing of active spark jobs  

Solution: 

1. Reduced the cadence of source status recalculation from “every 5 sec per active UI user” to “recalculate when any source process changed state” 
2. Persisted source status in postgres table, and added it to source list UI page  
3. For source inputs and process tabs, changed data refresh mechanism from 5 second timer to “refresh only when source status changed” 
4. For top level process page, kept the 5 second refresh cadence and modified the code to only resend results when process data changed 
5. Added indexing on process\_history table to optimize refresh queries when viewed from source-&gt;process tab 

UI/UX 

Combined Source List Filter 

![Previous Source Filters](data:image/png;base64,)

In previous versions, source filters were available as individual dropdown selections. This not only crowded the button bar, but also made it impossible to stack multiple values for one filter type. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Now, source filters have been combined into two dropdowns: filter type, and filter sources. Users will select a filter type in the first dropdown before selecting a value in the second. The filter sources dropdown also enables users to search for values; this is especially useful for filter types that have many values. 

Once a filter value has been selected, a filter tag appears in the brand-new Active Filters: bar. These tags display both the filter type and filter value. Users can have multiple filter tags of varying types or even the same filter type with different values! 

As shown above, there are three active filters, two are group filters and the other a refresh type. Only sources with a refresh type of key and group of either group value are displayed. This flexibility allows users to create even more filter combinations than before. 

These filter tags can be removed by clicking their individual close icon. The tags also alternate between three Intellio DataOPS colors in order to better distinguish them from one another. 

A final note on this new feature, just as with source names, users need not fear of losing their filter tags. Should a user navigate to a source then hit the back button, all their previously selected filter tags will still be present and displayed. Happy filtering! 

New Features 

Delta Lake Output 

Users can now create and write to Databricks Delta Lake tables using the Output features in the UI. Before, the only way to create a Hive output in Databricks was by using the Virtual Output feature - however, the virtual output only created a view in the Databricks metastore. Now, by using the Delta Lake Output feature, users can create a persisted Hive output table in Databricks that is optimized with Delta Lake capabilities. 

To get started working with Delta Lake Output, create a connection in your DataOps environment that points at an existing database in your Databricks hive metastore. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Once a connection is created, create the Output and Mappings in the same way that other Table outputs are created. Users can specify partition ordinals for columns in their mappings to control partitioning and partition column order. Columns that have partition ordinals on them will have a “PX” icon on their header, with X being the ordinal number configured in the column details. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Schema restrictions on Delta Lake tables require us to overwrite the table when certain changes are made in the Output Mappings page. These changes are: partition ordinal changes, name changes, and data type changes. If the table does need to be overwritten due to these changes, don’t fear! There is logic to kick off output processes on all output channels that are connected to the output, so that the table will be completely refreshed without a loss of any data from its channels. 

Learn more about Databricks Delta Lake here: [https://docs.databricks.com/delta/index.html](https://docs.databricks.com/delta/index.html) 

External API Routes 

We’ve exposed 4 routes on our API application that can be accessed with a new Auth0 Machine to Machine application that is created by Terraform in the DataOps Auth0 tenant. The application will be called &lt;environment&gt;-External-&lt;client&gt;. Request a JWT token using the Client ID and Client Secret of the new external application and these routes will be accessible. 

Routes 

POST /external/source-pull/&lt;source-id&gt; 

* Triggers a source to do a “pull now” and begin the Ingestion process 

POST /external/inputs-filtered 

* Returns list of inputs filtered by limit and effective status 
* Requires body: {"source\_id": &lt;source-id&gt;, "limit": &lt;integer&gt;, "effective\_filter": &lt;boolean&gt;} 

GET /external/sources 

* Returns unfiltered list of sources in the environment 

GET /external/sources-filtered-by-name/&lt;filter&gt; 

* Returns list of sources with filter condition applied to the source name field. The filter parameter should be a section of the source name, for example, if you were looking for all sources that had demo in the name, you would call /external/sources-filtered-by-name/demo 

Specify Target Database for Virtual Outputs 

Virtual Outputs can now be created in any database in the Databricks metastore. Use the “View Database” parameter in the Output settings page to define the database. If left blank, the database will be defaulted to the DataOps hub database.
